'''Differential display''' (also referred to as '''DDRT-PCR''' or '''DD-PCR''') is a laboratory technique that allows a researcher to compare and identify changes in gene expression at the [[mRNA]] level between two or more eukaryotic cell samples.<ref name=Peale2001rev>{{cite journal|last1=Peale FV|first1=Jr|last2=Gerritsen|first2=ME|title=Gene profiling techniques and their application in angiogenesis and vascular development|journal=The Journal of Pathology|date=September 2001|volume=195|issue=1|pages=7–19|pmid=11568887|doi=10.1002/path.888}}</ref>  It was the most commonly used method to compare expression profiles of two eukaryotic cell samples in the 1990s.<ref name=Peale2001rev/> By 2000, differential display was superseded by [[DNA microarray]] approaches.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pandey|first1=A|last2=Mann|first2=M|title=Proteomics to study genes and genomes|journal=Nature|date=15 June 2000|volume=405|issue=6788|pages=837–46|pmid=10866210|doi=10.1038/35015709}}</ref>

In differential display, first all the RNA in each sample is [[reverse transcription|reverse transcribed]] using a set of [[Directionality (molecular biology)|3′]] "anchored [[Primer (molecular biology)|primers]]" (having a short sequence of deoxy-thymidine nucleotides at the end) to create a [[cDNA library]] for each sample, followed by [[PCR]] amplification using arbitrary 3′ primers for cDNA strand amplification together with anchored 3′ primers for RNA strand amplification, identical to those used to create the library; about forty arbitrary primers is the optimal number to transcribe almost all of the mRNA. The resulting transcripts are then separated by [[electrophoresis]] and visualized, so that they can be compared.<ref name=Peale2001rev/>   The method was prone to error due to different mRNAs migrated into single bands, differences in less abundant mRNAs getting drowned by more abundant mRNAs,<ref name=Peale2001rev/> sensitivity to small changes in cell culture conditions, and a tendency to amplify 3&prime; fragments rather than full mRNAs, and the necessity to use about 300 primers to catch all the mRNA.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Reece|first1=Richard J.|title=Analysis of genes and genomes|date=2004|publisher=Wiley|location=Chichester|isbn=978-0-470-84380-2}}</ref>{{rp|316–317}}  The method was first published in ''Science'' in 1992.<ref name=Peale2001rev/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Liang|first1=P|last2=Pardee|first2=AB|title=Differential display of eukaryotic messenger RNA by means of the polymerase chain reaction|journal=Science|date=14 August 1992|volume=257|issue=5072|pages=967–71|pmid=1354393}}</ref>

