'''Francis Russell, Marquess of Tavistock''' (27 September 1739 – 22 March 1767) was a [[United Kingdom|British]] politician and the eldest son of the [[John Russell, 4th Duke of Bedford|4th Duke of Bedford]] and his second wife Hon. Gertrude Leveson-Gower.

From 1759 to 1761, he sat in the [[Irish House of Commons]] as [[British Whig Party|Whig]] [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Armagh Borough (Parliament of Ireland constituency)|Armagh Borough]] and then in the [[British House of Commons]] for [[Bedfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Bedfordshire]] until 1767.

He was elected as a Bailiff to the board of the [[Bedford Level Corporation]] in 1761, a position he held until his death.<ref> {{cite book|title=History of the Drainage of the Great Level of the Fens Called ..., Volume 1|first = Samuel|last= Wells|page=500}} </ref>

Lord Tavistock died in 1767, after falling from his horse while out hunting. On 8 June 1764, he had married [[Elizabeth Russell, Marchioness of Tavistock|Lady Elizabeth Keppel]], the youngest child of the [[Willem Anne van Keppel, 2nd Earl of Albemarle|2nd Earl of Albemarle]]. They had three sons:

*[[Francis Russell, 5th Duke of Bedford]] (1765–1802)
*[[John Russell, 6th Duke of Bedford]] (1766–1839)
*[[Lord William Russell (aristocrat)|Lord William Russell]] (1767–1840)

Their eldest son succeeded his grandfather as 5th [[Duke of Bedford]] in 1771.

